('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:153008e9', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which sentence uses ‘soler + infinitive’ correctly for a habit?", "options": ["Suelo salir los sábados por la noche", "Suelo salgo los sábados por la noche", "Soy salir los sábados por la noche", "Suelo saliendo los sábados por la noche"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "soler is followed by an infinitive: suelo salir. B conjugates salir again, C uses the wrong verb (soy), D uses the gerund (saliendo)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:5a39fd6b', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which is correct for ‘I do (go) swimming’?", "options": ["Hago natación", "Juego a natación", "Juego al natación", "Hace natación yo"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Swimming isn’t a ‘jugar’ sport — use hacer + noun: hago natación. Adding ‘a’/‘al’ or swapping the subject are the traps."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:a41de7e7', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does ‘dar un paseo’ mean?", "options": ["to go for a walk", "to give a present or gift", "to pass an exam easily", "to pay for a bus ticket"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "dar un paseo = to go for a walk. False-friend traps: ‘dar’ (to give) and ‘paseo’ sounding like ‘pasar’/‘pagar’."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:70dc7356', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "<span data-say=\"Mi equipo ganó la copa después de un partido muy justo.\" data-listen></span><br>Listen. What happened?", "options": ["My team won the cup after a very fair match", "My team lost the cup after a very fair match", "My team won the cup after a very unfair match", "My team won a medal after a friendly match"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘ganó la copa’ = won the cup; ‘un partido muy justo’ = a very fair match. Traps flip win/lose, flip fair/unfair, or swap cup→medal."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:294d4235', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How do you say ‘It cost me a lot of money’?", "options": ["Me costó mucho dinero", "Me costará mucho dinero", "Me cuesta mucho dinero ayer", "Me costaba mucho dinero mañana"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "‘costó’ is the preterite (a completed cost). B shifts to the future; C and D mix a present/imperfect verb with a past or future time word, which cannot go together."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:95718a78', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does ‘se hizo una herida’ mean?", "options": ["he/she got injured", "he/she felt very happy", "he/she scored a goal", "he/she won the trophy easily"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "hacerse una herida = to get injured/hurt yourself. The distractors describe unrelated, positive match outcomes."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:c4be9bfb', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which sentence means ‘I like trying new activities’?", "options": ["Me gusta probar actividades nuevas", "Me gusta probar actividades viejas", "No me gusta probar actividades nuevas", "Me gustaba probar actividades nuevas"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "probar actividades nuevas = to try new activities. Traps swap new→old, add a negative, or shift into the imperfect (used to like)."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:mcq:261159bd', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does ‘controlar los nervios’ mean?", "options": ["to control your nerves", "to lose all your nerves completely", "to celebrate winning a match", "to injure yourself badly before playing"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "controlar los nervios = to control your nerves (stay calm). The distractors invent unrelated match outcomes."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:tf:18ecbc2c', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘jugar al fútbol’ needs the word ‘al’ before a ball sport."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "jugar takes a+el=al before a ball/racquet sport: jugar al fútbol."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:tf:70c64698', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘hacer natación’ is used because swimming is not a ‘jugar’ sport."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Non-ball activities use hacer + noun: hago natación."}'::jsonb),
('spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out:tf:87ba22a9', 'spanish', 'spanish:4-1-sport-hobbies-and-going-out', '4.1 Sport, Hobbies and Going Out', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "‘Me gusta jugar’ should really be ‘Me gustan jugar’ because jugar is an activity."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Before a single infinitive, gustar stays singular: me gusta jugar. ‘gustan’ is only for plural nouns."}'::jsonb)
